Minikube Setup and Kubernetes Steps

Open a terminal (PowerShell or CMD).

Start Minikube with a driver:
Hyper-V: minikube start --driver=hyperv
Docker: minikube start --driver=docker

Verify Minikube is running:
minikube status

Use kubectl to interact with the cluster:
minikube kubectl -- get pods -A

Open the Minikube dashboard (optional):
minikube dashboard

Check versions:
minikube version
kubectl version --client

Troubleshooting commands:
Check logs: minikube logs
Check updates: minikube update-check
Update Minikube: minikube update

Start Minikube cluster (automation step):
minikube start

Create a deployment in Kubernetes:
kubectl create deployment mynginx --image=nginx

If deployment already exists, update image:
kubectl set image deployment/myngnix nginx=nginx:latest

Verify deployment and pods:
kubectl get deployments
kubectl get pods
kubectl describe pods

Expose the deployment as a service:
kubectl expose deployment mynginx --type=NodePort --port=80 --target-port=80

Scale the deployment:
kubectl scale deployment mynginx --replicas=4

Check service:
kubectl get service mynginx

Access the Nginx app using port forwarding:
kubectl port-forward svc/mynginx 8081:80
Access at: http://localhost:8081

If port forwarding fails, use Minikube tunnel:
Start tunnel: minikube tunnel
Get service URL: minikube service mynginx --url

Open the Minikube dashboard:
minikube dashboard

Delete deployment and service:
kubectl delete deployment mynginx
kubectl delete service mynginx

Stop Minikube:
minikube stop

Delete the Minikube cluster:
minikube delete
